Last year, I was the first Ph.D student from an Interdisciplinary Ethics & Social Justice Program to be offered an opportunity to present. ("Integral Frames: Interdisciplinary Tools
Supporting Cannabis Research");
as well as receive a travel award by the International Cannabinoid Research Society (ICRS) Symposium.  I was also the first student to crowdfund their way to the ICRS.  As a social scientist, advocate, and patient I was thrilled!  The trip to Baveno, Italy was incredible--and although it was terribly difficult given my limited budget and due to the fact I was incredibly ill, the learning experience was life-changing.I wrote about one of the many connections I made with scientific researchers:http://www.ladybud.com/2014/09/17/cannabis-beats-placebo-cbd-promising-for-treating-brain-damage-in-preemies/A month after Ladybud published this article scientists from the U.S. confirmed this neuro-protective benefit.  I've also presented this story and many others involving clinical research in cannabinoid medicine affecting many health conditions: cancer, Alzheimer's, PTS, seizure-disorders, among others!This year I've been invited back to the 2015 ICRS Symposium being held in late June in Nova Scotia on the Acadia University Campus.  In addition, I will receive a $500 travel award!  Good news, since those funds will only cover registration for the symposium; that means I need to raise another $1,500 to cover travel, food, and lodging.  Though I've been making a lot of exciting press announcements about the launch of The eCS Therapy Center--a national 501(c)(3) organization, the funding we have acquired is all ear-marked for infrastructure,.  I will not be drawing a real paycheck for quite sometime and my financial aid (student leans) will not fund until weeks after this incredible academic opportunity has been achieved.  I need help!Please support this campaign!
